<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-421-645  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 421 645.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 10 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australian government steps up computer security checks.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     GovernmentAustraliaFraudConsultantsSecurityComputer crimes.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AUSTRALIAN GOVERNMENT STEPS UP COMPUTER SECURITY CHECKS CANBERRA, AUSTRALIA,1990 JUL 6 (NB) -- Australian federal government agencies are increasingsecurity levels following revelations that computer abuse has risen sharplyin the last year.andP;  Some estimates place the total level of fraud against thegovernment at more than US$3 billion last year.andM;As is the case in most parts of the world, computer fraud is often unreportedand is handled internally.andP;  This is often due to embarrassment, fear ofclients becoming uneasy, or simply arrogance, according to security advisers.andO;Just why the Australian government is loath to release details is unclear.andM;Increasingly, government agencies are bringing in external consultants andauditors in to give the all-clear to new systems.andP;  As one consultant toldNewsbytes, &quot;We went in to check out their new personnel system and found anumber of scams including ghosts on the payroll, checks being raised to fakeaccounts and personal orders being made on departmental accounts.&quot; Theconsultant would not name the agency involved.andM;(Paul Zucker/19900706)</TEXT></DOC>